The bounce logic then amplifies the wall normal component of velocity—doubling it for regular bounces, quadrupling it for players hitting force fields, and handling special double-bounce flags. The velocity is then scaled and added back to apply the bounce effect.

For force field bounces specifically, there's a velocity cap check to prevent objects from going too fast. If a weapon bounced, its orientation gets reoriented to match its new velocity direction. Then the collision check loops again to see if the object hits anything else.

The C implementation has some key differences from what OCaml would do: it explicitly checks for force field flags in the tilemap data, uses a separate velocity-capping mechanism for force field bounces, and supports a double-bounce flag that OCaml doesn't have.

