```

Comparing the OCaml bounce calculation...

The OCaml implementation only respects the PF_BOUNCE flag and doesn't account for forcefields, PF_BOUNCES_TWICE, velocity capping on forcefield bounces, player extra bounce mechanics, weapon orientation updates, or the interaction between PF_STICK and forcefields where the forcefield should take precedence. Looking at the stick handling, it seems the OCaml code does set stuck objects and zero velocity, but I need to verify how it handles the forcefield override case. I'm noticing some critical differences in how the OCaml and C implementations handle force field interactions—specifically, the OCaml version doesn't check the `forcefield_bounce` flag before applying the PF_STICK behavior, which means objects would stick instead of bounce off in certain scenarios where C would bounce them. I should trace through the D2 OCaml physics code more carefully to see what other bounce-related flags and velocity checks might be missing.

